  "contentHtml": "\n                                    \n                                                                                    <ul>\n                                                                                                                                                    <li><a href=\"/agency/12345678/Reuters\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Reuters</a></li>\n                                                                                            </ul>\n                                                                                <ul>\n                                                                                            <li>Published On Apr 9, 2026 at 07:36 AM IST</li>\n                                                                                                                                </ul>\n                                    \n                                \n\n                    <!-- Display video article in news article for the custom next story -->\n                    \n                    <!-- Modifying the body placing embeds,promoslots,related etc.-->\n                                        <figure><img src=\"/images/default.jpg\" alt=\"\"></figure>Bengaluru: Lab equipment maker <a href=\"/tag/waters\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Waters</a> said on Wednesday the U.S. Food and Drug Administration has cleared its <a href=\"/tag/at-home+cervical+cancer+screening\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">at-home cervical cancer screening</a> kit for use with an approved <a href=\"/tag/hpv+test\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">HPV test</a>, potentially improving early detection ‌and reducing deaths ⁠from ⁠the cancer.<a href=\"/tag/waters\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Waters</a> said about 60% of cervical ​cancers occur in people who are not screened or ​are screened less often than recommended.<!-- PROMOSLOT_M -->The self-collection kit, tested with BD's Onclarity HPV assay, ​is designed to detect all ⁠high-risk types of ‌human papillomavirus, Waters added.Patients can ​collect a sample at home ⁠and mail it to a laboratory, with ​results shared with their healthcare provider, the ​company said.\n                            <p>Advt\n                            </p>\n\n                              \n                                                         \n                        The World Health Organization estimates that persistent HPV infection of the cervix, if untreated, causes around 95% of cervical cancers.<!-- PROMOSLOT_M -->The company said it worked ‌with the U.S. National Cancer Institute to confirm the accuracy of home ​sample collection.Waters said ⁠it is setting up partnerships to make the kit available nationwide by prescription in the coming ​months.The company said the kit is expected to be covered by private insurance as well as federal programs such as Medicare and Medicaid. <!-- PROMOSLOT_M -->(Reporting by Sahil Pandey in Bengaluru; Editing by Vijay Kishore)                    \n                                                                    \n                                                                \n                                <ul>\n                                    \n\n                                                                        <li><a href=\"/agency/12345678/Reuters\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Reuters</a></li>\n                                </ul>\n                                <ul>\n                                    <!-- <li> Updated On Apr 9, 2026 at 07:36 AM IST</li> -->\n                                    <li>Published On Apr 9, 2026 at 07:36 AM IST</li>\n                                    <!-- <li class=\"desktop-view\">1 min read</li> -->\n                                </ul>\n                            \n                                        \n\n                    \n\n                    <!-- Comment Section -->\